  "parameters": {
    "temperature": null,
    "max_tokens": 4096,
    "seed": null
  },
  "cold_question_prompt": "What is a lexical reachability?",
  "cold_response_verbatim_chat_a": "**Lexical reachability** means that a name/variable/function is accessible from a piece of code because of the program’s **lexical scope**—that is, based on where the code is written in the source text.\n\nA variable is **lexically reachable** if it is declared in:\n\n1. the current scope, or  \n2. an enclosing outer scope,  \n\nand it has not been hidden by another declaration with the same name.\n\nExample in JavaScript:\n\n```js\nlet globalVar = 1;\n\nfunction outer() {\n  let outerVar = 2;\n\n  function inner() {\n    let innerVar = 3;\n\n    console.log(globalVar); // reachable\n    console.log(outerVar);  // reachable\n    console.log(innerVar);  // reachable\n  }\n}\n```\n\nInside `inner`, all three variables are lexically reachable because they are in the current or enclosing lexical scopes.\n\nBut:\n\n```js\nfunction a() {\n  let x = 10;\n}\n\nfunction b() {\n  console.log(x); // not lexically reachable\n}\n```\n\nHere, `x` is not lexically reachable from `b` because `b` is not written inside `a`.\n\nIn short: **lexical reachability is about what identifiers code can access by looking outward through its statically nested scopes.**",
  "cold_response_verbatim_chat_b": "**Lexical reachability** is the idea that a name, variable, function, or declaration is “reachable” from a particular point in source code based on the program’s **lexical structure** — that is, its written/nested scopes.\n\nIn simpler terms:  \nA variable is lexically reachable if the code location you are in is allowed to refer to it by normal scope rules.\n\nExample in JavaScript:\n\n```js\nfunction outer() {\n  let x = 10;\n\n  function inner() {\n    console.log(x); // x is lexically reachable here\n  }\n}\n\nconsole.log(x); // x is not lexically reachable here\n```\n\nInside `inner`, the variable `x` is reachable because `inner` is written inside `outer`, and inner scopes can access outer scopes. Outside `outer`, `x` is not reachable.\n\nSo **lexical reachability** is about visibility determined by where code is written, not by what happens at runtime.",
  "boundary_test_prompts": [
    "How does \"lexical reachability\" differ from vocabulary coverage?",
    "How does \"lexical reachability\" differ from graph reachability?",
    "How does \"lexical reachability\" differ from in-context learning capability?"
  ],
  "cold_boundary_responses": [
    "They’re different concepts, even though both use the word **lexical**.\n\n### Lexical reachability\n\nIn programming, **lexical reachability** is about whether a name is accessible from a particular place in the source code because of lexical/static scope.\n\nExample:\n\n```js\nfunction outer() {\n  let x = 10;\n\n  function inner() {\n    console.log(x); // x is lexically reachable here\n  }\n}\n```\n\nHere, `x` is reachable from `inner` because `inner` is written inside `outer`.\n\nSo lexical reachability answers:\n\n> “Can this piece of code access this identifier based on where it is written?”\n\nIt is usually **scope-based** and often **yes/no**.\n\n---\n\n### Vocabulary coverage\n\n**Vocabulary coverage** is usually a language/NLP concept. It measures how much of a text is covered by a known vocabulary, dictionary, tokenizer, or model.\n\nExample:\n\n```text\nText: \"The cat sat on the mat\"\nKnown vocabulary: {the, cat, sat, on}\n```\n\nCovered words: `The`, `cat`, `sat`, `on`, `the`  \nNot covered: `mat`\n\nVocabulary coverage might be:\n\n```text\n5 out of 6 words = 83.3%\n```\n\nSo vocabulary coverage answers:\n\n> “What percentage of the words in this text are included in my vocabulary?”\n\nIt is usually **set/statistics-based** and expressed as a **percentage**.\n\n---\n\n### Main difference\n\n| Concept | Domain | Meaning |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Lexical reachability** | Programming / scope analysis | Whether an identifier can be accessed from a location in code |\n| **Vocabulary coverage** | Linguistics / NLP / language learning | How much of a text’s words are known or represented |\n\nIn short:\n\n> **Lexical reachability is about access to names in code; vocabulary coverage is about how many words in a text are known or included in a vocabulary.**",
    "**Lexical reachability** and **graph reachability** are related in spirit—both ask whether something can be “reached”—but they apply to different structures.\n\n## Lexical reachability\n\n**Lexical reachability** is about whether an identifier, such as a variable or function name, is accessible from a location in source code based on **lexical/static scope**.\n\nExample:\n\n```js\nfunction outer() {\n  let x = 10;\n\n  function inner() {\n    console.log(x); // x is lexically reachable here\n  }\n}\n```\n\nHere, `x` is lexically reachable from inside `inner` because `inner` is written inside the scope where `x` is declared.\n\nLexical reachability answers:\n\n> “Can this code refer to this name based on the nesting of scopes in the source code?”\n\nIt depends on things like:\n\n- nested scopes,\n- declarations,\n- imports,\n- shadowing,\n- visibility rules.\n\n---\n\n## Graph reachability\n\n**Graph reachability** is a general graph theory concept. It asks whether one node can be reached from another by following edges.\n\nExample:\n\n```text\nA → B → C\nD → E\n```\n\nFrom `A`, node `C` is reachable because there is a path:\n\n```text\nA → B → C\n```\n\nBut `E` is not reachable from `A`.\n\nGraph reachability answers:\n\n> “Is there a path from one node to another in this graph?”\n\nIt applies to many domains, such as:\n\n- networks,\n- dependency graphs,\n- control-flow graphs,\n- call graphs,\n- web links,\n- state machines.\n\n---\n\n## Main difference\n\n| Concept | Domain | What is being reached? | Basis of reachability |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Lexical reachability** | Programming languages / scope | Identifiers like variables or functions | Static lexical scope rules |\n| **Graph reachability** | Graph theory / algorithms | Nodes in a graph | Paths along edges |\n\n---\n\n## Relationship between them\n\nLexical reachability can sometimes be **modeled using a graph**.\n\nFor example, scopes can be represented as nodes:\n\n```text\nglobal scope → outer scope → inner scope\n```\n\nThen checking whether `inner` can access `x` may involve walking outward through a scope graph.\n\nBut conceptually:\n\n> **Graph reachability is the general idea of finding paths in a graph. Lexical reachability is a specific programming-language idea about whether names are accessible through lexical scope.**",
    "**Lexical reachability** and **in-context learning capability** are very different ideas.\n\n## Lexical reachability\n\n**Lexical reachability** is about whether a name, variable, function, or symbol is accessible from a location in code because of **lexical/static scope**.\n\nExample:\n\n```js\nfunction outer() {\n  let x = 10;\n\n  function inner() {\n    console.log(x); // x is lexically reachable here\n  }\n}\n```\n\nHere, `x` is lexically reachable from `inner` because `inner` is written inside `outer`.\n\nIt answers:\n\n> “Can this piece of code access this identifier according to the language’s scope rules?”\n\nIt is usually:\n\n- static,\n- rule-based,\n- deterministic,\n- about programming language structure.\n\n---\n\n## In-context learning capability\n\n**In-context learning capability** is usually discussed in large language models. It means a model can infer a task, pattern, or behavior from examples or instructions provided in the prompt, without changing its internal weights.\n\nExample prompt:\n\n```text\nTranslate English to French.\n\ncat -> chat\ndog -> chien\nhouse -> maison\n\nbook ->\n```\n\nA model with in-context learning capability may infer that it should output:\n\n```text\nlivre\n```\n\nIt answers:\n\n> “Can the model learn or infer what to do from the context it was given?”\n\nIt is usually:\n\n- probabilistic,\n- behavior-based,\n- dependent on prompt contents,\n- associated with AI/LLMs,\n- not based on formal scope rules.\n\n---\n\n## Main difference\n\n| Concept | Domain | Meaning |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Lexical reachability** | Programming languages | Whether an identifier is accessible from a place in code |\n| **In-context learning capability** | AI / language models | Whether a model can infer a task or pattern from prompt examples |\n\nIn short:\n\n> **Lexical reachability is about what names code can access by static scope rules. In-context learning is about what a model can infer from examples or instructions in its input context.**"
  ],
  "introduction_prompt": "Here is the canonical definition of \"lexical reachability\": Lexical Reachability is the metric that operationalizes the Token-Substrate Hypothesis as the gap between a model's cold-state distinguishability of a term against named near-neighbors and its post-introduction distinguishability after a single-sentence definition is provided in context, scored per (model × term × near-neighbor) cell. Acknowledge that you have read it.",
  "model_acknowledgement": "Acknowledged. I have read the canonical definition of **lexical reachability**:\n\nIt is a metric operationalizing the Token-Substrate Hypothesis as the gap between a model’s cold-state distinguishability of a term against named near-neighbors and its post-introduction distinguishability after a single-sentence definition is provided in context, scored per *(model × term × near-neighbor)* cell.",
  "post_intro_boundary_responses": [
    "**Vocabulary coverage** asks:  \n> “Is this word/term in the vocabulary, or can the system represent it?”\n\n**Lexical reachability** asks:  \n> “Can the model distinguish this term from nearby named alternatives, and how much does that improve after the term is introduced with a definition?”\n\nSo the difference is:\n\n| Concept | What it measures | Unit of concern |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Vocabulary coverage** | Whether a term is present, recognized, tokenized, or included in some vocabulary/resource | Term-level inclusion |\n| **Lexical reachability** | The gap between a model’s cold-state distinguishability of a term and its distinguishability after an in-context definition | Model × term × near-neighbor behavioral score |\n\nIn other words, a term can have **vocabulary coverage** but still have low **lexical reachability**. The model may tokenize or have seen the term, yet fail to distinguish it from near-neighbors. Conversely, a rare or novel term may have poor prior coverage but become highly reachable after a concise definition.\n\nVocabulary coverage is mostly about **availability of lexical forms**.  \nLexical reachability is about **model-specific discriminative uptake** after contextual introduction.",
    "**Graph reachability** asks:\n\n> “Is there a path from node A to node B in a graph?”\n\n**Lexical reachability**, by your canonical definition, asks:\n\n> “How much does a model’s ability to distinguish a term from named near-neighbors improve after the term is introduced with a one-sentence definition, compared to its cold-state distinguishability?”\n\nSo the difference is:\n\n| Concept | Domain | What is being measured |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Graph reachability** | Graph theory / networks | Whether one node can be reached from another via edges |\n| **Lexical reachability** | Model evaluation / lexical semantics | The gap between cold-state and post-definition distinguishability of a term against near-neighbors |\n\nGraph reachability is usually a **structural property**: given a graph, node B is either reachable from node A or not, sometimes with path length or cost added.\n\nLexical reachability is a **behavioral metric**: given a model, a term, and a near-neighbor, it measures how distinguishable the term is before and after contextual definition.\n\nIn short:\n\n> **Graph reachability is about paths between nodes. Lexical reachability is about a model’s ability to discriminate a term from nearby alternatives after lexical introduction.**",
    "**In-context learning capability** asks:\n\n> “Can a model use information provided in the prompt to perform a task better or differently?”\n\n**Lexical reachability**, by the canonical definition, asks:\n\n> “For a specific term and named near-neighbor, how much does the model’s distinguishability improve after the term is introduced with a single-sentence definition, relative to its cold-state distinguishability?”\n\nSo the difference is:\n\n| Concept | Scope | What it measures |\n|---|---|---|\n| **In-context learning capability** | Broad model behavior | The model’s general ability to adapt to information, examples, instructions, or demonstrations in the prompt |\n| **Lexical reachability** | Specific lexical-semantic metric | The gap between cold-state and post-introduction distinguishability of a term against a named near-neighbor |\n\nLexical reachability uses an in-context intervention — the single-sentence definition — but it is not the same as general in-context learning. It is a **particular evaluation of lexical uptake and discrimination**.\n\nA model could have strong general in-context learning ability but still show low lexical reachability for a particular term if it fails to distinguish that term from a near-neighbor. Conversely, a model might show good lexical reachability for a term because the definition makes the contrast clear, without necessarily implying broad in-context learning competence.\n\nIn short:\n\n> **In-context learning is the general ability to use prompt-provided information; lexical reachability is a specific metric measuring how much a definition improves a model’s discrimination of a term from near-neighbors.**"
  ],
  "recold_response_verbatim": "**Lexical reachability** usually means whether a name, variable, function, or declaration can be accessed from a particular place in the source code based on the program’s **lexical structure** — that is, its written/nested scope layout.\n\nIn simpler terms:\n\n> A variable is lexically reachable if the code at that location is allowed to refer to it according to the language’s scoping rules.\n\nExample in JavaScript:\n\n```js\nfunction outer() {\n  let x = 10;\n\n  function inner() {\n    console.log(x); // x is lexically reachable here\n  }\n}\n\nconsole.log(x); // x is not lexically reachable here\n```\n\nInside `inner`, the variable `x` is reachable because `inner` is written inside `outer`, where `x` is declared.\n\nThis is called **lexical** because it depends on the code’s textual/nested structure, not on the runtime call stack.\n\nIt is related to **lexical scope**, where scopes are determined by where code is written. It contrasts with ideas like **dynamic reachability**, which depend on runtime behavior.",
  "recold_boundary_responses": [
    "**Lexical reachability** and **vocabulary coverage** are different ideas, even though both use “lexical.”\n\n| Term | Main field | Meaning |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Lexical reachability** | Programming / formal languages | Whether a name or declaration can be accessed from a specific place in code based on lexical scope rules |\n| **Vocabulary coverage** | NLP / language learning / corpus linguistics | How much of a text’s words are included in a known vocabulary or word list |\n\n### Lexical reachability\n\nThis is about **scope**.\n\nExample:\n\n```js\nfunction outer() {\n  let x = 10;\n\n  function inner() {\n    console.log(x); // x is lexically reachable here\n  }\n}\n\nconsole.log(x); // x is not lexically reachable here\n```\n\nHere, `x` is reachable inside `inner` because of the program’s nested structure.\n\nSo lexical reachability asks:\n\n> “Can this piece of code legally refer to that variable/function/name?”\n\n---\n\n### Vocabulary coverage\n\nThis is about **word knowledge or word inclusion**.\n\nFor example, suppose a learner knows these words:\n\n```text\nthe, cat, sat, on, mat\n```\n\nAnd the sentence is:\n\n```text\nThe cat sat on the mat.\n```\n\nThe learner has nearly 100% vocabulary coverage.\n\nBut for:\n\n```text\nThe cat leapt onto the windowsill.\n```\n\ncoverage is lower if they do not know `leapt`, `onto`, or `windowsill`.\n\nSo vocabulary coverage asks:\n\n> “What percentage of words in this text are known, recognized, or included in a vocabulary list?”\n\n---\n\n### Key difference\n\n**Lexical reachability** is about **accessibility of identifiers in code**.\n\n**Vocabulary coverage** is about **how many words in a text are represented or known**.\n\nSo:\n\n```text\nlexical reachability = Can this name be accessed here?\nvocabulary coverage = How much of this text’s vocabulary is covered?\n```",
    "**Lexical reachability** and **graph reachability** both involve the idea of “can something be reached?”, but they apply in different contexts.\n\n| Term | Main area | Meaning |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Lexical reachability** | Programming languages / compilers | Whether an identifier is accessible from a location in source code based on lexical scope rules |\n| **Graph reachability** | Graph theory / algorithms | Whether one node can be reached from another by following edges in a graph |\n\n### Lexical reachability\n\nThis is about **scope in code**.\n\nExample:\n\n```js\nfunction outer() {\n  let x = 10;\n\n  function inner() {\n    console.log(x); // x is lexically reachable here\n  }\n}\n\nconsole.log(x); // x is not lexically reachable here\n```\n\nThe variable `x` is reachable inside `inner` because `inner` is written inside the lexical scope of `outer`.\n\nSo lexical reachability asks:\n\n> “Can this part of the program legally refer to that variable or declaration?”\n\nIt depends on the program’s **textual structure**, such as blocks, functions, modules, and nesting.\n\n---\n\n### Graph reachability\n\nThis is about **paths in a graph**.\n\nExample:\n\n```text\nA → B → C\nD → E\n```\n\nFrom `A`, node `C` is reachable because there is a path:\n\n```text\nA → B → C\n```\n\nBut `E` is not reachable from `A`.\n\nSo graph reachability asks:\n\n> “Is there a path from one node to another?”\n\nIt depends on **nodes and edges**, not source-code scope.\n\n---\n\n### Key difference\n\n```text\nlexical reachability = accessibility by scope rules in source code\ngraph reachability   = accessibility by paths through graph edges\n```\n\nThat said, compilers or static analysis tools may **represent lexical scopes as a graph**, and then compute reachability using graph algorithms. But conceptually, lexical reachability is a programming-language scope concept, while graph reachability is a general mathematical/computational concept.",
    "**Lexical reachability** and **in-context learning capability** are very different concepts.\n\n| Term | Main area | Meaning |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Lexical reachability** | Programming languages / compilers | Whether an identifier, such as a variable or function, can be accessed from a particular place in source code based on lexical scope |\n| **In-context learning capability** | Machine learning / large language models | A model’s ability to infer a task from examples or instructions given in the prompt, without updating its parameters |\n\n### Lexical reachability\n\nThis is about **scope rules in code**.\n\nExample:\n\n```js\nfunction outer() {\n  let x = 10;\n\n  function inner() {\n    console.log(x); // x is lexically reachable here\n  }\n}\n\nconsole.log(x); // x is not lexically reachable here\n```\n\nHere, `x` is reachable inside `inner` because `inner` is written inside `outer`.\n\nLexical reachability asks:\n\n> “Can this part of the code legally refer to that name?”\n\nIt is determined by the program’s textual structure: blocks, functions, modules, and nesting.\n\n---\n\n### In-context learning capability\n\nThis is about **how an AI model uses information in its prompt**.\n\nExample prompt:\n\n```text\nTranslate English to French:\n\ncat -> chat\ndog -> chien\nhouse -> maison\n\nbook ->\n```\n\nA model with in-context learning capability may infer that it should translate `book` into French and answer:\n\n```text\nlivre\n```\n\nThe model has not been retrained. It is using the examples in the current context to infer the pattern.\n\nIn-context learning asks:\n\n> “Can the model learn or infer what to do from the prompt itself?”\n\n---\n\n### Key difference\n\n```text\nlexical reachability      = Can code access this variable/name here?\nin-context learning       = Can a model infer a task from prompt examples?\n```\n\nLexical reachability is a **static programming-language concept**.\n\nIn-context learning capability is a **behavioral property of AI models**, especially large language models."
  ],
