        "user": "How does \"lexical reachability\" differ from in-context learning capability?",
        "assistant": "**Lexical reachability** and **in-context learning capability** are very different ideas.\n\n## Lexical reachability\n\n**Lexical reachability** is about whether a name, variable, function, or symbol is accessible from a location in code because of **lexical/static scope**.\n\nExample:\n\n```js\nfunction outer() {\n  let x = 10;\n\n  function inner() {\n    console.log(x); // x is lexically reachable here\n  }\n}\n```\n\nHere, `x` is lexically reachable from `inner` because `inner` is written inside `outer`.\n\nIt answers:\n\n> “Can this piece of code access this identifier according to the language’s scope rules?”\n\nIt is usually:\n\n- static,\n- rule-based,\n- deterministic,\n- about programming language structure.\n\n---\n\n## In-context learning capability\n\n**In-context learning capability** is usually discussed in large language models. It means a model can infer a task, pattern, or behavior from examples or instructions provided in the prompt, without changing its internal weights.\n\nExample prompt:\n\n```text\nTranslate English to French.\n\ncat -> chat\ndog -> chien\nhouse -> maison\n\nbook ->\n```\n\nA model with in-context learning capability may infer that it should output:\n\n```text\nlivre\n```\n\nIt answers:\n\n> “Can the model learn or infer what to do from the context it was given?”\n\nIt is usually:\n\n- probabilistic,\n- behavior-based,\n- dependent on prompt contents,\n- associated with AI/LLMs,\n- not based on formal scope rules.\n\n---\n\n## Main difference\n\n| Concept | Domain | Meaning |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Lexical reachability** | Programming languages | Whether an identifier is accessible from a place in code |\n| **In-context learning capability** | AI / language models | Whether a model can infer a task or pattern from prompt examples |\n\nIn short:\n\n> **Lexical reachability is about what names code can access by static scope rules. In-context learning is about what a model can infer from examples or instructions in its input context.**",
