        "user": "How does \"lexical reachability\" differ from vocabulary coverage?",
        "assistant": "**Lexical reachability** and **vocabulary coverage** are different ideas, even though both use “lexical.”\n\n| Term | Main field | Meaning |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Lexical reachability** | Programming / formal languages | Whether a name or declaration can be accessed from a specific place in code based on lexical scope rules |\n| **Vocabulary coverage** | NLP / language learning / corpus linguistics | How much of a text’s words are included in a known vocabulary or word list |\n\n### Lexical reachability\n\nThis is about **scope**.\n\nExample:\n\n```js\nfunction outer() {\n  let x = 10;\n\n  function inner() {\n    console.log(x); // x is lexically reachable here\n  }\n}\n\nconsole.log(x); // x is not lexically reachable here\n```\n\nHere, `x` is reachable inside `inner` because of the program’s nested structure.\n\nSo lexical reachability asks:\n\n> “Can this piece of code legally refer to that variable/function/name?”\n\n---\n\n### Vocabulary coverage\n\nThis is about **word knowledge or word inclusion**.\n\nFor example, suppose a learner knows these words:\n\n```text\nthe, cat, sat, on, mat\n```\n\nAnd the sentence is:\n\n```text\nThe cat sat on the mat.\n```\n\nThe learner has nearly 100% vocabulary coverage.\n\nBut for:\n\n```text\nThe cat leapt onto the windowsill.\n```\n\ncoverage is lower if they do not know `leapt`, `onto`, or `windowsill`.\n\nSo vocabulary coverage asks:\n\n> “What percentage of words in this text are known, recognized, or included in a vocabulary list?”\n\n---\n\n### Key difference\n\n**Lexical reachability** is about **accessibility of identifiers in code**.\n\n**Vocabulary coverage** is about **how many words in a text are represented or known**.\n\nSo:\n\n```text\nlexical reachability = Can this name be accessed here?\nvocabulary coverage = How much of this text’s vocabulary is covered?\n```",
