        "assistant": "**Lexical reachability** and **graph reachability** both involve the idea of “can something be reached?”, but they apply in different contexts.\n\n| Term | Main area | Meaning |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Lexical reachability** | Programming languages / compilers | Whether an identifier is accessible from a location in source code based on lexical scope rules |\n| **Graph reachability** | Graph theory / algorithms | Whether one node can be reached from another by following edges in a graph |\n\n### Lexical reachability\n\nThis is about **scope in code**.\n\nExample:\n\n```js\nfunction outer() {\n  let x = 10;\n\n  function inner() {\n    console.log(x); // x is lexically reachable here\n  }\n}\n\nconsole.log(x); // x is not lexically reachable here\n```\n\nThe variable `x` is reachable inside `inner` because `inner` is written inside the lexical scope of `outer`.\n\nSo lexical reachability asks:\n\n> “Can this part of the program legally refer to that variable or declaration?”\n\nIt depends on the program’s **textual structure**, such as blocks, functions, modules, and nesting.\n\n---\n\n### Graph reachability\n\nThis is about **paths in a graph**.\n\nExample:\n\n```text\nA → B → C\nD → E\n```\n\nFrom `A`, node `C` is reachable because there is a path:\n\n```text\nA → B → C\n```\n\nBut `E` is not reachable from `A`.\n\nSo graph reachability asks:\n\n> “Is there a path from one node to another?”\n\nIt depends on **nodes and edges**, not source-code scope.\n\n---\n\n### Key difference\n\n```text\nlexical reachability = accessibility by scope rules in source code\ngraph reachability   = accessibility by paths through graph edges\n```\n\nThat said, compilers or static analysis tools may **represent lexical scopes as a graph**, and then compute reachability using graph algorithms. But conceptually, lexical reachability is a programming-language scope concept, while graph reachability is a general mathematical/computational concept.",
